<Document>
<name>Going-to-the-Sun Road</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Going-to-the-Sun Road</h2><p><i>Montana, USA · Glacier National Park, West Glacier to St Mary</i></p><p><b>An engineering miracle of 1932 blasted across a vertical cliff face at 2,026 m.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>70 km (43 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>2 hrs no stops; full day with hikes</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>Late June–mid September (full road typically open ~3 months)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Vehicle size limits past Avalanche (no rigs &gt;21 ft long or 8 ft wide); snow until July; mountain goats on road; no guardrails on some sections</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>189</td></tr></table><hr><p>Begun 1921, opened 1932; the central section across the Garden Wall was blasted by laborers dangling on ropes. Logan Pass at 2,026 m is the spine of the continent — water leaving the parking lot flows to either the Pacific, the Atlantic, or the Hudson Bay. Vehicle reservations are required in summer. Closes after the first heavy snow, often by mid-October; full reopening is rarely before late June. The road is named for Going-to-the-Sun Mountain, named in turn for a Blackfeet legend.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Lake McDonald</b> — 16 km glacial lake with multicolored pebbles. Stop at the lodge — 1913 Swiss-chalet style, lobby fireplace from local stone.</li><li><b>Avalanche Lake trailhead</b> — 3.4 km hike (one-way) to a turquoise lake ringed by waterfalls dropping from hanging valleys.</li><li><b>The Loop</b> — Only switchback on the entire road. Pull off; trailhead for Granite Park Chalet (a 1914 backcountry hut).</li><li><b>Bird Woman Falls</b> — 150 m cascade from a hanging cirque, visible across the valley. Best in early summer.</li><li><b>Logan Pass</b> — 2,026 m, Continental Divide. Mountain goats and bighorn sheep common on the visitor-center deck. Hidden Lake trailhead — 4.4 km round trip to a true alpine basin.</li><li><b>Jackson Glacier overlook</b> — The only glacier visible directly from the road. It will be gone within a generation; in 1850 the park had ~80 glaciers, today ~25.</li><li><b>Wild Goose Island</b> — Tiny island in St Mary Lake — the iconic Glacier postcard view. Best light early morning.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
